# Motion and interaction

Source of truth: motion tokens and helpers live in `src/index.css` (`@theme` motion block, `.transition-surface`, `.pressable`).

## Do this

- **Interactive controls** (buttons, tabs, pills, dense list rows): use `transition-surface` and, when a physical press helps, `pressable` together. Override duration with Tailwind only when the control is smaller or snappier (e.g. `duration-150`).
- **Easing by intent**: user-driven appear/settle → `ease-out` (default surface uses `--ease-out`). Elements already on screen that move or morph → `ease-in-out`. Hover-only color/border softening → `ease-hover` when it reads better than `ease-out`.
- **Durations**: micro feedback ~100–150ms; standard UI ~150–250ms; modals/drawers ~200–300ms. Stay under ~300ms unless it is rare, marketing-style motion.
- **Performance**: prefer animating **`transform`** and **`opacity`** for continuous motion; avoid animating layout (`width`/`height`/`margin`/`padding`) for polish unless there is no jank.
- **Paired surfaces**: overlay + panel share the **same** duration and easing.
- **Reduced motion**: respect `prefers-reduced-motion`. The project has a global shorten rule; do not add long decorative motion without a reduced-motion path. Radix overlays may use `motion-reduce:transition-none` where already established.
- **Touch / hover**: use `@media (hover: hover) and (pointer: fine)` for hover-only transforms if they would fire oddly on touch (optional pattern; not every hover needs it).

## Avoid this

- One-off `transition-all` on new components without a reason (harder to keep GPU-friendly and consistent).
- **New random** duration/easing constants in components instead of theme defaults and Tailwind utilities.

## Quick reference

```tsx
className={cn('transition-surface pressable', className)}
// snappier segment controls:
className={cn('transition-surface pressable duration-150', className)}
```

`Button` and the sidebar nav rows already follow this pattern—match them for new controls.
